def convert_notebook(title, output='html'):
    convert = sp.run(f'jupyter nbconvert {title}.ipynb --to {output} --output {title}.{output}'.split(' '))
    if convert.returncode == 0:
        display_md(f'Jupyter notebook `{title}` converted successfully.')
    else:
        display_md(f'Error: encountered problem converting Jupyter notebook `{title}`')

df_self = df_joint[df_joint['self_vs_other'] == 'self']

df_blind = df_self[df_self['group'] == 'blind'].groupby(
    ['adjective', 'color']).mean().sort_values(
    ['adjective', 'color']).reset_index()
df_sighted = df_self[df_self['group'] == 'sighted'].groupby(
    ['adjective', 'color']).mean().sort_values(
    ['adjective', 'color']).reset_index()

df_diff = df_blind[[
    'adjective',
    'color',
    'cosine_fic_z',
    'viz_vs_ling_mean',
    'neither_vs_both_mean',
]]
df_diff['blind_rating'] = df_blind['rating']
df_diff['sighted_rating'] = df_sighted['rating']
df_diff['rating_diff'] = df_diff['sighted_rating'] - df_diff['blind_rating']

Correlations between visual/linguistic/association ratings and the original blind/sighted participants' color/dimension ratings¶

In [9]:
def print_corr(df, col1, col2):
    r = pearsonr(df[col1], df[col2])
    print(f'r({col1}, {col2}) = {r[0]:.2f} (p = {r[1]:.3f})')
    return

print('Correlation with rating differences between ratings from blind and sighted participants:')
print_corr(df_diff, 'viz_vs_ling_mean', 'rating_diff')
print_corr(df_diff, 'neither_vs_both_mean', 'rating_diff')

print('\nCorrelation with ratings from blind participants:')
print_corr(df_diff, 'viz_vs_ling_mean', 'sighted_rating')
print_corr(df_diff, 'neither_vs_both_mean', 'sighted_rating')

print('\nCorrelation with ratings from blind participants:')
print_corr(df_diff, 'viz_vs_ling_mean', 'blind_rating')
print_corr(df_diff, 'neither_vs_both_mean', 'blind_rating')

Correlation with rating differences between ratings from blind and sighted participants:

r(neither_vs_both_mean, rating_diff) = 0.08 (p = 0.143)

Correlation with ratings from blind participants:
r(viz_vs_ling_mean, sighted_rating) = -0.24 (p = 0.000)

Correlation with ratings from blind participants:

r(neither_vs_both_mean, blind_rating) = 0.40 (p = 0.000)

Scatterplots¶

Visual vs. linguistic and rating difference between blind and sighted¶

We would expect this to be negative if sighted people give higher association ratings to color/adjective associations that are rated as more visual in nature than blind people do. (In other words, a more visual rating predicts lower association score for blind than for sighted people in the Saysani data once you split the color/dimension ratings into color/adjective association scores.)

In [10]:
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize': (6, 6)})

def annot(ax, df, x, y, label):
    for i, row in df.iterrows():
        if ((row[x] == df[x].max()) or (row[x] == df[x].min())) or ((row[y] == df[y].max()) or (row[y] == df[y].min())):
            ax.text(row[x] + .01, row[y], row[label])

ax = sns.scatterplot(x='viz_vs_ling_mean', y='rating_diff',
                     data=df_diff, hue='color', palette=colordict, legend=False)

sns.regplot(x='viz_vs_ling_mean', y='rating_diff', scatter=False,
                     data=df_diff, ax=ax);

ax.set(xlabel='(more visual)             source of knowledge             (more linguistic)',
       ylabel='difference in\n' +
       '(blind stronger)             association ratings          (sighted stronger)',
       xlim=[.05, .95], ylim=[-3, 3])

annot(ax, df_diff, 'viz_vs_ling_mean', 'rating_diff', 'adjective')

def annotate(df, color, dimension, x=0, y=0, ha='right', va='center'):
    plt.text(df.loc[(df['color'] == color) & (df['adjective'] == dimension), 'viz_vs_ling_mean'].values[0] + x,
             df.loc[(df['color'] == color) & (df['adjective'] == dimension), 'rating_diff'].values[0] + y,
             f'{color} / {dimension}', ha=ha, va=va, fontdict={'size': 'small'})
    
def annotate_line(df, color, dimension, x=0, y=0):
    xpos = df.loc[(df['color'] == color) & (df['adjective'] == dimension), 'viz_vs_ling_mean'].values[0]
    ypos = df.loc[(df['color'] == color) & (df['adjective'] == dimension), 'rating_diff'].values[0]
    plt.plot((xpos, xpos + x), (ypos, ypos + y), color='black', alpha=.2)

annotate(df_diff, 'green', 'ripe', 0, .05, 'center', 'bottom')
annotate(df_diff, 'black', 'dirty', 0, -.1, 'center', 'top')
annotate(df_diff, 'green', 'jealous', 0, -.1, 'center', 'top')

annotate(df_diff, 'red', 'fast', -.15, -.2)
annotate(df_diff, 'green', 'relaxed', .25, 1.2, 'center', 'bottom')
annotate(df_diff, 'orange', 'tense', .2, .8, 'center', 'bottom')

annotate_line(df_diff, 'red', 'fast', -.14, -.2)
annotate_line(df_diff, 'green', 'relaxed', .25, 1.2)
annotate_line(df_diff, 'orange', 'tense', .2, .8)

Neither vs. both and rating difference between blind and sighted¶

We expect these two to be essentially uncorrelated: There is no reason to believe that association strength rated orthogonally (literally!) to the visual/linguistic nature of the association should have any differential impact on how blind and sighted people rate the associations.
